slang = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/sentiment-data/Sentiment_Data/slangs.csv')
slang_map = dict(zip(slang['slang'], slang['meaning']))

def replace_slangs(text):
    if isinstance(text, str):
            for word in text.split():
                if word in slang_map:
                    text = text.replace(word, slang_map[word])
    return text

def replace_emoticons(text):
    emoticon = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/sentiment-data/emoticons.csv')
    emoticon_map = dict(zip(emoticon['emoticon'], emoticon['meaning']))
    for emot in emoticon_map:
        text = text.replace(emot, ' ' + emoticon_map[emot] + ' ')
    return text

def handle_negations(text):
    negation_patterns = ["n't", "not", "never", "no"]
    words = text.split()
    for i in range(len(words)):
        if words[i].lower() in negation_patterns:
            if i+1 < len(words):
                words[i+1] = "NOT_" + words[i+1] + " "
    return ' '.join(words)

# Function to clean text
def clean_text(text):
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = re.sub(r'@\w+', ' ', text)              # Remove mentions
        text = re.sub(r'#', ' ', text)                 # Remove hashtags
        text = re.sub(r'\w+:\/\/\S+', ' ', text)           # Remove hyperlinks
        text = re.sub(r'\S*@\S*\s?', ' ', text)        # Remove email addresses
        text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', ' ', text)           # Remove punctuation
        text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z]+', ' ', text)           # Remove all non-English characters
        text = handle_negations(text)                  # Handle negations
        text = replace_emoticons(text)                 # Replace emoticons by their meanings
        text = emoji.demojize(text)                     # Replace emojis by their meanings
        text = replace_slangs(text)                    # Replace slangs by their meanings
        text = re.sub(r'\d+', ' ', text)             # Remove numbers
        text = text.lower()                            # Convert to lowercase
        
    return text

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import os

# Define some parameters
max_vocab_size = 5000
max_seq_length = 30

# Initialize the lemmatizer and stopwords
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=max_vocab_size)

# Your existing preprocess_text function
def preprocess_text(tweet):
    tokens = word_tokenize(tweet)  # Tokenize
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word.lower() not in stop_words]  # Remove stopwords
    tokens = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in tokens]  # Lemmatize
    tweet = ' '.join(tokens)
    return tweet

# Preprocess the texts
X_train = [preprocess_text(tweet) for tweet in X_train]
X_test = [preprocess_text(tweet) for tweet in X_test]

# Initialize the tokenizer
tokenizer = Tokenizer()
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(X_train)

# Convert texts to sequences
X_train_seq = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_train)
X_test_seq = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_test)

# Pad sequences to ensure uniform input size
X_train_pad = pad_sequences(X_train_seq, maxlen=max_seq_length)
X_test_pad = pad_sequences(X_test_seq, maxlen=max_seq_length)

# Plot the PCA embeddings
def plot_pca_embeddings(embeddings, labels, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    for i in np.unique(labels):
        idxs = np.where(labels == i)
        plt.scatter(embeddings[idxs, 0], embeddings[idxs, 1], label=f'Class {i}', alpha=0.5)
    plt.xlabel('PCA Component 1')
    plt.ylabel('PCA Component 2')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Plot train embeddings
plot_pca_embeddings(X_train_pca, np.array(y_train), 'PCA of Train Set Embeddings')

class PositionalEncoding(tf.keras.layers.Layer):
    def __init__(self, d_model, max_len):
        super(PositionalEncoding, self).__init__()
        self.pos_encoding = self.positional_encoding(max_len, d_model)
    
    def positional_encoding(self, position, d_model):
        angle_rads = self.get_angles(np.arange(position)[:, np.newaxis],
                                     np.arange(d_model)[np.newaxis, :],
                                     d_model)
        angle_rads[:, 0::2] = np.sin(angle_rads[:, 0::2])
        angle_rads[:, 1::2] = np.cos(angle_rads[:, 1::2])
        pos_encoding = angle_rads[np.newaxis, ...]
        return tf.cast(pos_encoding, dtype=tf.float32)
    
    def get_angles(self, pos, i, d_model):
        angle_rates = 1 / np.power(10000, (2 * (i//2)) / np.float32(d_model))
        return pos * angle_rates

    def call(self, inputs):
        return inputs + self.pos_encoding[:, :tf.shape(inputs)[1], :]

def transformer_model(vocab_size, d_model, num_heads, ff_dim, num_layers, max_seq_length, l2_reg=0.01, dropout_rate=0.1):
    initializer = tf.keras.initializers.GlorotUniform()
    
    inputs = tf.keras.Input(shape=(max_seq_length,))
    embedding_layer = tf.keras.layers.Embedding(vocab_size, d_model)(inputs)
    pos_encoding_layer = PositionalEncoding(d_model, max_seq_length)(embedding_layer)

    for _ in range(num_layers):
        attn_output = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=num_heads, key_dim=d_model)(pos_encoding_layer, pos_encoding_layer)
        attn_output = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate)(attn_output)
        out1 = tf.keras.layers.LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)(pos_encoding_layer + attn_output)

        ffn_output = tf.keras.layers.Dense(ff_dim, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                           kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(out1)
        ffn_output = tf.keras.layers.Dense(d_model, kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                           kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(ffn_output)
        ffn_output = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate)(ffn_output)
        pos_encoding_layer  = tf.keras.layers.LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)(out1 + ffn_output)

    outputs = tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling1D()(pos_encoding_layer)
    outputs = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(dropout_rate)(outputs)
    outputs = tf.keras.layers.Dense(20, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                    kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(outputs)
    outputs = tf.keras.layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax', kernel_initializer=initializer,
                                    kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(outputs)
    
    return tf.keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, ConfusionMatrixDisplay, roc_curve, auc, classification_report
from sklearn.preprocessing import label_binarize
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def evaluate_model_performance(model, X_test_pad, y_test, history):
    """
    Evaluates the performance of a classification model by printing a classification report,
    plotting accuracy and loss curves, confusion matrix, and ROC AUC curves.
    
    Parameters:
    model: Trained model to evaluate
    X_test_pad: Padded test data features
    y_test: True labels for the test data
    history: Training history object containing accuracy and loss values
    
    Returns:
    None
    """
    # Predict on validation data
    y_test_pred = np.argmax(model.predict(X_test_pad), axis=-1)

    # Generate classification report
    print("Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred, target_names=['Negative', 'Neutral', 'Positive']))

    # Plot training & validation accuracy values
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper left')

    # Plot training & validation loss values
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title('Model loss')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper left')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Predict labels for the test set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_pad)
    y_pred_classes = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)

    # Compute the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_classes)

    # Binarize the labels for ROC AUC
    y_test_binarized = label_binarize(y_test, classes=[0, 1, 2])
    y_pred_binarized = label_binarize(y_pred_classes, classes=[0, 1, 2])

    # Compute ROC curve and ROC area for each class
    fpr = dict()
    tpr = dict()
    roc_auc = dict()
    for i in range(3):
        fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_test_binarized[:, i], y_pred[:, i])
        roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])

    # Plot confusion matrix and combined ROC AUC
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(18, 6))

    # Plot confusion matrix
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=['Negative', 'Neutral', 'Positive'])
    disp.plot(cmap=plt.cm.Blues, ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title('Confusion Matrix')

    # Plot ROC AUC for each class in the same graph
    ax = axes[1]
    colors = ['blue', 'green', 'red']
    for i, color in zip(range(3), colors):
        ax.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], color=color, lw=2, label='Class {0} (area = {1:0.2f})'.format(i, roc_auc[i]))
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    ax.set_xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    ax.set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    ax.set_title('ROC AUC for All Classes')
    ax.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    ax.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

from collections import defaultdict, Counter
import numpy as np

# Function to preprocess and pad sequences for the model
def predict_fn(texts):
    sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(texts)
    padded_sequences = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=max_seq_length)
    return model.predict(padded_sequences)

# Apply LIME
explainer = lime.lime_text.LimeTextExplainer(class_names=['Negative', 'Neutral', 'Positive'])

# Initialize dictionaries to store feature weights for each class
feature_weights = {'Negative': defaultdict(float), 'Neutral': defaultdict(float), 'Positive': defaultdict(float)}

# Number of samples to explain
num_samples = 1000
sample_indices = np.random.choice(len(X_test_texts), num_samples, replace=False)

# Loop through each sample and get LIME explanations
for i in sample_indices:
    explanation = explainer.explain_instance(X_test_texts[i], predict_fn, num_features=10)
    explanation_map = explanation.as_list()
    
    # Get the predicted class
    predicted_class = np.argmax(predict_fn([X_test_texts[i]])[0])
    class_name = ['Negative', 'Neutral', 'Positive'][predicted_class]
    
    # Aggregate feature weights for the predicted class
    for feature, weight in explanation_map:
        feature_weights[class_name][feature] += weight
In[]:
# Summarize the results to find the most influential words for each class
for class_name, weights in feature_weights.items():
    print(f"Top features for class {class_name}:")
    for feature, weight in Counter(weights).most_common(10):
        print(f"{feature}: {weight:.4f}")
    print("\n")

The model continues to demonstrate strong performance, achieving a high training accuracy of 87.44% by the 11th epoch. However, the validation accuracy is 78.17%, which, along with a validation loss of 0.7051, indicates some overfitting.

Observations

  • The overall accuracy is 75%.
  • Precision, recall, and f1-score are well-balanced across the "Negative," "Neutral," and "Positive" classes.
  • The "Positive" class shows the highest recall and f1-score, indicating that the model is particularly effective at identifying positive sentiments.

Next Steps

To further improve model performance and reduce overfitting, we can consider:

  • Increasing the dropout rate or adding more dropout layers.
  • Applying stronger regularization techniques.
  • Conducting further hyperparameter tuning.
  • Evaluating the impact of early stopping to prevent overfitting during training.
  • It appears that the words "freedom" and "freedomconvoy" have high influence across all three classes. We should investigate these instances more closely and determine if additional preprocessing is required to better distinguish between the classes.
